he examin'd, others have, particularly
<HI>Lewvenhoeck,</HI> as may be &s;een in his Letters,
and in the <HI>Tran&s;actions;</HI> Where he tells us
not only of his having di&s;covered the&s;e <HI>Ani|malculs</HI>
in the <HI>Uterus</HI> and in the <HI>Tubae Fallo|pianae,</HI>
but de&s;cribes their fir&s;t Degree of
<HI>Transformation.</HI> As for <HI>C. O's</HI> <GAP DESC="FOREIGN">,
it is much the &s;ame with his <HI>difficiliora</HI> <GAP DESC="FOREIGN">,
(<HI>Tarrugo's</HI> Old Way of <HI>Tau|tologizing</HI>)
to inform tho&s;e whom he and
his <HI>Tran&s;lator</HI> have not Occa&s;ion to tell, by
